Subject: material entity

Note: Material entity [snap:MaterialEntity] subsumes object [snap:Object], fiat object part [snap:FiatObjectPart], and object aggregate [snap:ObjectAggregate], which assume a three level theory of granularity, which is inadequate for some domains, such as biology.

Subject: material entity

Subject: part of
Value: For continuants: C part_of C' if and only if: given any c that instantiates C at a time t, there is some c' such that c' instantiates C' at time t, and c *part_of* c' at t. For processes: P part_of P' if and only if: given any p that instantiates P at a time t, there is some p' such that p' instantiates P' at time t, and p *part_of* p' at t. (Here *part_of* is the instance-level part-relation.)

Subject: biological_process
Value: A biological process is the execution of a genetically-encoded biological module or program. It consists of all the steps required to achieve the specific biological objective of the module. A biological process is accomplished by a particular set of molecular functions carried out by specific gene products (or macromolecular complexes), often in a highly regulated manner and in a particular temporal sequence.

Subject: biological_process
Value: A process that emerges from two or more causally-connected macromolecular activities and has evolved to achieve a biological objective.

Subject: textual definition
Value:
2012-04-05: 
Barry Smith

The official OBI definition, explaining the meaning of a class or property: 'Shall be Aristotelian, formalized and normalized. Can be augmented with colloquial definitions'  is terrible.

Can you fix to something like:

A statement of necessary and sufficient conditions explaining the meaning of an expression referring to a class or property.

Alan Ruttenberg

Your proposed definition is a reasonable candidate, except that it is very common that necessary and sufficient conditions are not given. Mostly they are necessary, occasionally they are necessary and sufficient or just sufficient. Often they use terms that are not themselves defined and so they effectively can't be evaluated by those criteria. 

On the specifics of the proposed definition:

We don't have definitions of 'meaning' or 'expression' or 'property'. For 'reference' in the intended sense I think we use the term 'denotation'. For 'expression', I think we you mean symbol, or identifier. For 'meaning' it differs for class and property. For class we want documentation that let's the intended reader determine whether an entity is instance of the class, or not. For property we want documentation that let's the intended reader determine, given a pair of potential relata, whether the assertion that the relation holds is true. The 'intended reader' part suggests that we also specify who, we expect, would be able to understand the definition, and also generalizes over human and computer reader to include textual and logical definition. 

Personally, I am more comfortable weakening definition to documentation, with instructions as to what is desirable. 

We also have the outstanding issue of how to aim different definitions to different audiences. A clinical audience reading chebi wants a different sort of definition documentation/definition from a chemistry trained audience, and similarly there is a need for a definition that is adequate for an ontologist to work with.  @en

Subject: accelerationTime
Value:
The time needed to accelerate the vehicle from a given start velocity to a given target velocity.

Typical unit code(s): SEC for seconds

  • Note: There are unfortunately no standard unit codes for seconds/0..100 km/h or seconds/0..60 mph. Simply use \"SEC\" for seconds and indicate the velocities in the name of the QuantitativeValue, or use valueReference with a QuantitativeValue of 0..60 mph or 0..100 km/h to specify the reference speeds.
@en

Subject: fuelConsumption
Value:
The amount of fuel consumed for traveling a particular distance or temporal duration with the given vehicle (e.g. liters per 100 km).

  • Note 1: There are unfortunately no standard unit codes for liters per 100 km. Use unitText to indicate the unit of measurement, e.g. L/100 km.
  • Note 2: There are two ways of indicating the fuel consumption, fuelConsumption (e.g. 8 liters per 100 km) and fuelEfficiency (e.g. 30 miles per gallon). They are reciprocal.
  • Note 3: Often, the absolute value is useful only when related to driving speed (\"at 80 km/h\") or usage pattern (\"city traffic\"). You can use valueReference to link the value for the fuel consumption to another value.
@en

Subject: fuelEfficiency
Value:
The distance traveled per unit of fuel used; most commonly miles per gallon (mpg) or kilometers per liter (km/L).

  • Note 1: There are unfortunately no standard unit codes for miles per gallon or kilometers per liter. Use unitText to indicate the unit of measurement, e.g. mpg or km/L.
  • Note 2: There are two ways of indicating the fuel consumption, fuelConsumption (e.g. 8 liters per 100 km) and fuelEfficiency (e.g. 30 miles per gallon). They are reciprocal.
  • Note 3: Often, the absolute value is useful only when related to driving speed (\"at 80 km/h\") or usage pattern (\"city traffic\"). You can use valueReference to link the value for the fuel economy to another value.
@en

Subject: payload
Value:
The permitted weight of passengers and cargo, EXCLUDING the weight of the empty vehicle.

Typical unit code(s): KGM for kilogram, LBR for pound

  • Note 1: Many databases specify the permitted TOTAL weight instead, which is the sum of weight and payload
  • Note 2: You can indicate additional information in the name of the QuantitativeValue node.
  • Note 3: You may also link to a QualitativeValue node that provides additional information using valueReference.
  • Note 4: Note that you can use minValue and maxValue to indicate ranges.
@en

Subject: roofLoad
Value:
The permitted total weight of cargo and installations (e.g. a roof rack) on top of the vehicle.

Typical unit code(s): KGM for kilogram, LBR for pound

  • Note 1: You can indicate additional information in the name of the QuantitativeValue node.
  • Note 2: You may also link to a QualitativeValue node that provides additional information using valueReference
  • Note 3: Note that you can use minValue and maxValue to indicate ranges.
@en

Subject: tongueWeight
Value:
The permitted vertical load (TWR) of a trailer attached to the vehicle. Also referred to as Tongue Load Rating (TLR) or Vertical Load Rating (VLR).

Typical unit code(s): KGM for kilogram, LBR for pound

  • Note 1: You can indicate additional information in the name of the QuantitativeValue node.
  • Note 2: You may also link to a QualitativeValue node that provides additional information using valueReference.
  • Note 3: Note that you can use minValue and maxValue to indicate ranges.
@en

Subject: weightTotal
Value:
The permitted total weight of the loaded vehicle, including passengers and cargo and the weight of the empty vehicle.

Typical unit code(s): KGM for kilogram, LBR for pound

  • Note 1: You can indicate additional information in the name of the QuantitativeValue node.
  • Note 2: You may also link to a QualitativeValue node that provides additional information using valueReference.
  • Note 3: Note that you can use minValue and maxValue to indicate ranges.
@en

Value: b is an object aggregate means: b is a material entity consisting exactly of a plurality of objects as member_parts at all times at which b exists. (axiom label in BFO2 Reference: [025-004])@en

Subject: generically dependent continuant
Value: b is a generically dependent continuant = Def. b is a continuant that g-depends_on one or more other entities. (axiom label in BFO2 Reference: [074-001])@en

Subject: part of
Value: a core relation that holds between a part and its whole@en

Subject: has part
Value: a core relation that holds between a whole and its part@en

Subject: realized in
Value: [copied from inverse property 'realizes'] to say that b realizes c at t is to assert that there is some material entity d & b is a process which has participant d at t & c is a disposition or role of which d is bearer_of at t& the type instantiated by b is correlated with the type instantiated by c. (axiom label in BFO2 Reference: [059-003])@en

Subject: realizes
Value: to say that b realizes c at t is to assert that there is some material entity d & b is a process which has participant d at t & c is a disposition or role of which d is bearer_of at t& the type instantiated by b is correlated with the type instantiated by c. (axiom label in BFO2 Reference: [059-003])@en

Subject: preceded by
Value: x is preceded by y if and only if the time point at which y ends is before or equivalent to the time point at which x starts. Formally: x preceded by y iff ω(y) <= α(x), where α is a function that maps a process to a start point, and ω is a function that maps a process to an end point.@en

Subject: precedes
Value: x precedes y if and only if the time point at which x ends is before or equivalent to the time point at which y starts. Formally: x precedes y iff ω(x) <= α(y), where α is a function that maps a process to a start point, and ω is a function that maps a process to an end point.@en

Subject: information content entity
Value: an information content entity is an entity that is generically dependent on some artifact and stands in relation of aboutness to some entity@en

Subject: is about
Value: is_about is a (currently) primitive relation that relates an information artifact to an entity.

Subject: is quality measurement of
Value: m is a quality measurement of q at t. When q is a quality, there is a measurement process p that has specified output m, a measurement datum, that is about q@en

Subject: is quality measured as
Value: inverse of the relation of is quality measurement of@en

Subject: is owned by
Value: a is owned by b if b has complete power over a. All rights and obligations of ownership are grounded in this (primitive) relation. The claims and obligations of ownership can be partially transferred to a third party by the owner, b.@en

Subject: regulator role
Value: a regulatory role involved with making and/or enforcing relevant legislation and governmental orders@en

Subject: regulatory role
Value: a role which inheres in material entities and is realized in the processes of making, enforcing or being defined by legislation or orders issued by a governmental body.@en

Subject: material supplier role
Value: a role realized through the process of supplying materials such as animal subjects, reagents or other materials used in an investigation.@en

Subject: investigation
Value: a planned process that consists of parts: planning, study design execution, documentation and which produce conclusion(s).@en

Subject: responsible party role
Value: a study personnel role played by a party who is accountable for the execution of a study component and can make decisions about the conduct of the study@en

Subject: principal investigator role
Value: a responsible party role played by a person responsible for the overall conduct of a study@en

Subject: specimen role
Value: a role borne by a material entity that is gained during a specimen collection process and that can be realized by use of the specimen in an investigation@en

Subject: zip
Value: zip is a format standard of a digital entity that is conformant with the PKWARE .ZIP file format specification  (http://www.pkware.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=59&Itemid=103/)@en

Subject: tar
Value: tar is a format standard of a digital entity that is conformant with the tape archive file format as standardized by POSIX.1-1998, POSIX.1-2001, or any other tar format compliant with the GNU tar specification. (http://www.gnu.org/software/tar/manual/)@en

Subject: planning
Value: a process of creating or modifying a plan specification@en

Subject: material transformation objective
Value: an objective specifiction that creates an specific output object from input materials.@en

Subject: manufacturing objective
Value: is the objective to manufacture a material of a certain function (device)@en

Subject: study design execution
Value: a planned process that carries out a study design

Subject: GenePattern software
Value: a software that provides access to more than 100 tools for gene expression analysis, proteomics, SNP analysis and common data processing tasks.

Subject: service provider role
Value: is a role which inheres in a person or organization and is realized in in a planned process which provides access to training, materials or execution of protocols for an organization or person

Subject: leave one out cross validation method
Value: is a data transformation :  leave-one-out cross-validation (LOOCV) involves using a single observation from the original sample as the validation data, and the remaining observations as the training data. This is repeated such that each observation in the sample is used once as the validation data

Subject: spacecraft module
Value: a self-contained unit of a spacecraft

Subject: gamma radiation
Value: electromagnetic radiation with photon energies greater than approximately 100 keV

Subject: inheres in
Value: a relation between a specifically dependent continuant (the characteristic) and any other entity (the bearer), in which the characteristic depends on the bearer for its existence.@en

Subject: inheres in
Value: a relation between a specifically dependent continuant (the dependent) and an independent continuant (the bearer), in which the dependent specifically depends on the bearer for its existence@en

Subject: has characteristic
Value: a relation between an independent continuant (the bearer) and a specifically dependent continuant (the dependent), in which the dependent specifically depends on the bearer for its existence

Subject: has characteristic
Value: a relation between an independent continuant (the bearer) and a specifically dependent continuant (the dependent), in which the dependent specifically depends on the bearer for its existence@en

Subject: participates in
Value: a relation between a continuant and a process, in which the continuant is somehow involved in the process

Subject: participates in
Value: a relation between a continuant and a process, in which the continuant is somehow involved in the process@en

Subject: has participant
Value: a relation between a process and a continuant, in which the continuant is somehow involved in the process

Subject: has participant
Value: a relation between a process and a continuant, in which the continuant is somehow involved in the process@en

Subject: function of
Value: a relation between a function and an independent continuant (the bearer), in which the function specifically depends on the bearer for its existence@en

Subject: quality of
Value: a relation between a quality and an independent continuant (the bearer), in which the quality specifically depends on the bearer for its existence@en

Subject: role of
Value: a relation between a role and an independent continuant (the bearer), in which the role specifically depends on the bearer for its existence@en

Subject: has function
Value: a relation between an independent continuant (the bearer) and a function, in which the function specifically depends on the bearer for its existence@en

Subject: has quality
Value: a relation between an independent continuant (the bearer) and a quality, in which the quality specifically depends on the bearer for its existence@en

Subject: has role
Value: a relation between an independent continuant (the bearer) and a role, in which the role specifically depends on the bearer for its existence@en

Subject: has disposition
Value: a relation between an independent continuant (the bearer) and a disposition, in which the disposition specifically depends on the bearer for its existence@en

Subject: derives from
Value: a relation between two distinct material entities, the new entity and the old entity, in which the new entity begins to exist when the old entity ceases to exist, and the new entity inherits the significant portion of the matter of the old entity@en

Subject: derives into
Value: a relation between two distinct material entities, the old entity and the new entity, in which the new entity begins to exist when the old entity ceases to exist, and the new entity inherits the significant portion of the matter of the old entity@en

Subject: has component process
Value: w 'has process component' p if p and w are processes,  w 'has part' p and w is such that it can be directly disassembled into into n parts p, p2, p3, ..., pn, where these parts are of similar type.

Subject: overlaps
Value: x overlaps y if and only if there exists some z such that x has part z and z part of y

Subject: in taxon
Value: x is in taxon y if an only if y is an organism, and the relationship between x and y is one of: part of (reflexive), developmentally preceded by, derives from, secreted by, expressed.

Subject: has component
Value: w 'has component' p if w 'has part' p and w is such that it can be directly disassembled into into n parts p, p2, p3, ..., pn, where these parts are of similar type.

Subject: regulates
Value: p regulates q iff p is causally upstream of q, the execution of p is not constant and varies according to specific conditions, and p influences the rate or magnitude of execution of q due to an effect either on some enabler of q or some enabler of a part of q.

Subject: negatively regulates
Value: p negatively regulates q iff p regulates q, and p decreases the rate or magnitude of execution of q.

Subject: positively regulates
Value: p positively regulates q iff p regulates q, and p increases the rate or magnitude of execution of q.

Subject: capable of part of
Value: c stands in this relationship to p if and only if there exists some p' such that c is capable_of p', and p' is part_of p.

Subject: has input
Value: p has input c iff: p is a process, c is a material entity, c is a participant in p, c is present at the start of p, and the state of c is modified during p.

Subject: acts upstream of
Value: c acts upstream of p if and only if c enables some f that is involved in p' and p' occurs chronologically before p, is not part of p, and affects the execution of p. c is a material entity and f, p, p' are processes.

Subject: acts upstream of or within
Value: c acts upstream of or within p if c is enables f, and f is causally upstream of or within p. c is a material entity and p is an process.

Subject: causally upstream of, positive effect
Value: p is causally upstream of, positive effect q iff p is casually upstream of q, and the execution of p is required for the execution of q.

Subject: causally upstream of, negative effect
Value: p is causally upstream of, negative effect q iff p is casually upstream of q, and the execution of p decreases the execution of q.

Subject: characteristic of part of
Value: q characteristic of part of w if and only if there exists some p such that q inheres in p and p part of w.

Subject: enables
Value: c enables p iff c is capable of p and c acts to execute p.

Subject: part of structure that is capable of
Value: this relation holds between c and p when c is part of some c', and c' is capable of p.

Subject: involved in
Value: c involved_in p if and only if c enables some process p', and p' is part of p

Subject: member of
Value: is member of is a mereological relation between a item and a collection.

Subject: has member
Value: has member is a mereological relation between a collection and an item.

Subject: indirectly positively regulates
Value: p indirectly positively regulates q iff p is indirectly causally upstream of q and p positively regulates q.

Subject: indirectly negatively regulates
Value: p indirectly negatively regulates q iff p is indirectly causally upstream of q and p negatively regulates q.

Subject: causally related to
Value: relation that links two events, processes, states, or objects such that one event, process, state, or object (a cause) contributes to the production of another event, process, state, or object (an effect) where the cause is partly or wholly responsible for the effect, and the effect is partly or wholly dependent on the cause.

Subject: causally upstream of
Value: p is causally upstream of q iff p is causally related to q, the end of p precedes the end of q, and p is not an occurrent part of q.

Subject: immediately causally upstream of
Value: p is immediately causally upstream of q iff p is causally upstream of q, and the end of p is coincident with the beginning of q.

Subject: causally upstream of or within
Value: p is 'causally upstream or within' q iff p is causally related to q, and the end of p precedes, or is coincident with, the end of q.

Subject: causally downstream of or within
Value: inverse of causally upstream of or within

Subject: involved in regulation of
Value: c involved in regulation of p if c is involved in some p' and p' regulates some p

Subject: involved in positive regulation of
Value: c involved in regulation of p if c is involved in some p' and p' positively regulates some p

Subject: involved in negative regulation of
Value: c involved in regulation of p if c is involved in some p' and p' negatively regulates some p

Subject: involved in or involved in regulation of
Value: c involved in or regulates p if and only if either (i) c is involved in p or (ii) c is involved in regulation of p

Subject: causal relation between processes
Value: p is causally related to q if and only if p or any part of p and q or any part of q are linked by a chain of events where each event pair is one where the execution of p influences the execution of q. p may be upstream, downstream, part of, or a container of q.

Subject: directly regulates
Value: p directly regulates q iff p is immediately causally upstream of q and p regulates q.

Subject: has part structure that is capable of
Value: s 'has part structure that is capable of' p if and only if there exists some part x such that s 'has part' x and x 'capable of' p

Subject: directly positively regulates
Value: p directly positively regulates q iff p is immediately causally upstream of q, and p positively regulates q.

Subject: directly negatively regulates
Value: p directly negatively regulates q iff p is immediately causally upstream of q, and p negatively regulates q.

Subject: acts upstream of, positive effect
Value: c 'acts upstream of, positive effect' p if c is enables f, and f is causally upstream of p, and the direction of f is positive

Subject: acts upstream of, negative effect
Value: c 'acts upstream of, negative effect' p if c is enables f, and f is causally upstream of p, and the direction of f is negative

Subject: indirectly causally upstream of
Value: p is indirectly causally upstream of q iff p is causally upstream of q and there exists some process r such that p is causally upstream of r and r is causally upstream of q.

Subject: indirectly regulates
Value: p indirectly regulates q iff p is indirectly causally upstream of q and p regulates q.

Subject: dataset catalog id
Value: This alphanumeric string is generated at data acquisition, and is used to uniquely identify the dataset.
